A **class** is a blueprint that defines fields (state) and methods (behavior). An **object** is a specific instance of a class created at runtime.

A class declaration includes:
- Fields to hold data
- A constructor to initialize the object
- Methods to expose behavior

```java
public class Car {
    String color;
    int speed;
    void accelerate() { speed += 10; }
}
```

Objects are created with `new`, which allocates memory and calls the constructor. Each object has its own copy of instance fields but shares method code with all instances of the class.

Classes support encapsulation by making fields `private` and exposing them through getter/setter methods, protecting internal state from unintended modification.

