Java 21 (preview) and later allow **unnamed classes** and **instance main methods** — simplifying beginner programs by removing the class and `static` boilerplate.

Traditional:
```java
public class Hello {
    public static void main(String[] args) { System.out.println("Hi"); }
}
```

Compact (Java 21+ preview):
```java
void main() {
    System.out.println("Hi");
}
```

This feature targets learners and scripting use cases. The launcher automatically wraps the file in an unnamed class. `System.out` can be replaced with the shorthand `println()` when `java.io.IO` is imported (Java 23+).

For production code, continue using named classes with `public static void main`.

