Java 21 finalized **pattern matching for switch**, allowing switch cases to match on type patterns and deconstruct objects.

```java
Object obj = 42;
String result = switch (obj) {
    case Integer i -> "int: " + i;
    case String s  -> "str: " + s;
    case null      -> "null";
    default        -> "other";
};
```

Guarded patterns add conditions with `when`:
```java
case Integer i when i > 0 -> "positive int";
```

This eliminates boilerplate chains of `instanceof` checks and casts, making code more readable and exhaustive (the compiler can verify all cases are handled for sealed types).

